<assessment id="u3_m1_rules6_tutor1">
   <title>Tutor</title>
   <page><question id="q1">
      <body>
         <p>According to pollingreport.com,
               a<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T190315-0500" content=" recent"?>
               poll conducted by FOX
               <?oxy_comment_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T190418-0500" comment="add the year of the poll after &quot;News,&quot; so that this doesn&apos;t become out of date. "?>News<?oxy_comment_end?>
               estimate<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T190438-0500"?>d<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T190438-0500" content="s"?>
               that on the issue of abortion, roughly 44% of registered voters in the
               <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T190452-0500"?>United
               States<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T190449-0500" content="US"?>
               are pro-choice, and roughly 47% are pro-life (the remaining 9% are undecided).</p>
         <p>What is the probability that two
               <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T190537-0500"?>simultaneously
               and <?oxy_insert_end?>randomly chosen registered voters are pro-life?</p>
      </body>
      <short_answer id="A"/>
      <part>
         <response input="A" match="*" score="1"/>
         <explanation>
            <p>Let L1 be the event that
                  <?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T190605-0500" content="the first "?>person
                  <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T190609-0500"?>1
                  <?oxy_insert_end?>is pro-life, and let L2 be the event that
                  <?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T190615-0500" content="the second "?>person
                  <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T190623-0500"?>2
                  <?oxy_insert_end?>is pro-life.</p>
            <p>We need to find P(L1 and L2). Since the two were chosen at random, L1 and L2 are
                  independent and we may use the
                  <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T191155-0500"?>M<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T191155-0500" content="m"?>ultiplication
                  <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T191159-0500"?>R<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T191158-0500" content="r"?>ule
                  for
                  <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T191201-0500"?>I<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T191201-0500" content="i"?>ndependent
                  <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T191204-0500"?>E<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T191203-0500" content="e"?>vents:</p>
            <p>P(L1 and L2)=P(L1)<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T191019-0500"?>
                  <?oxy_insert_end?>*<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T191020-0500"?>
                  <?oxy_insert_end?>P(L2)<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T191021-0500"?>
                  <?oxy_insert_end?>= .47<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T191024-0500"?>
                  <?oxy_insert_end?>*<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T191025-0500"?>
                  <?oxy_insert_end?>.47<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T191026-0500"?>
                  <?oxy_insert_end?>=<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T191027-0500"?>
                  <?oxy_insert_end?>.2209.</p>
         </explanation>
      </part>
   </question></page>
